description.value: Egyptian terracotta model of sword hilt. A fragmentary hilt of a model sword, with a ribbed handle terminating in a stud and, on each side, the head of a panther; the swell to the guard survives on one side, the rest is broken away: from its size it is probable that only the hilt was represented, not the whole sword. Although both animal heads are modelled in the round, only the front of the hilt is ribbed, the back being largely plain. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Orange-brown Nile silt with a reddish core and abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions (<1.5mm).

description.value:
Fragmentary plaster cast of a sculptor’s model or trial piece, depicting a king in relief.

The obverse of the plaster cast shows the side profile of a king, the top part of the crown now lost but likely representing the White Crown of Upper Egypt. His ear is carefully modelled, and his upper eyelid is delineated with a heavy ridge. The eyebrow is thin and slopes slightly downwards to meet the short cosmetic line emerging from the outer corner of the eye. His nose is short and the mouth is full with thick lips, The outer corner of the mouth is flat and the lower lip is sharply incised. The fleshiness of the face is conveyed at the mouth area, beside the nose, and around the jawline and neck. The right shoulder of the figure sits high on the body and is comparatively flat compared to the rounded face. Across this surface is a proportional square grid of both red and black ink. On the reverse the stone has been chipped and there are several small gouges within the centre.

A model sword and its scabbard, with a ribbed handle and quadruple-balled pommel, the guard of pedimental form enclosing a raised stud. The blade has been pared. The separate scabbard has reinforced edgings, each terminating in a loop at the bottom and plain horizontal mouldings, probably representing metal bindings; there is a loop for suspension on each side near the top. description.value: Wooden model coffin: faithfully reproducing an anthropoid coffin of the middle 18th Dynasty, with a prominent foot and the sides of the case positioned at a steep angle to the horizontal. The exterior is painted yellow, perhaps to imitate the gold leaf with which the richest coffins would have been covered. This probably also explains why the painter has omitted the figures and inscriptions found on most full-sized coffins, although care has been taken to add the details of the face, wig and collar. Four wooden pegs slotting into sockets along the edges enable the lid of the coffin to be held securely in place.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta model of shield with relief of young man. A plaque incorporating a shield with a large oval boss and vertical spine: it is not certain whether it is a small rectangular Gaulish shield or a truncated large oval one. On the moulding, dwarfed by the shield (a servant or slave?), stands a short-haired beardless man to right, wearing a himation draped across his body and over his left shoulder; he holds an edge of it with his lowered right hand. His right leg is lost from just above the ankle, and his left arm is held aloft, crossing the shield, the hand holding a bag-like object. On the left side of the shield, on the ground-line, stands a kalathos. The rear is concave and has a large applied hollow vertical feature, possibly a socket, swelling to a rounded top and with a finished edge below; a post-firing hole is pierced from the front into this feature. Pressed into a one-piece mould. Covered in a red slip that is thicker at the front. Brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and medium white inclusions (<2mm).

A mould-made model sword lacking its scabbard, with a ribbed handle with triple or quadruple balled pommel, the guard of pedimental form enclosing a raided stud. The blade has been pared. description.value: Egg-shaped model bell: with circular rim damaged at the back. The front of the bell is worked to represent the face of the god Bes, and at the top a small capital supports the god's plumes, behind which a hole has been pierced to allow the suspension of the bell. The god's ears are prominent at the sides. Above the capital at the back the faience is decorated with four wavy lines; below it, and not quite centrally placed, is a hole which may have been used to support a tongue. The back is decorated with a jackal head and two lizards, of which the tails almost meet at the damaged base of the bell.

description.value: Rough wooden model of a boat: the hull is fairly deep with a good beam; it is hollowed out to a realistic depth, so that the gunwales are 2.8cm high above the deck. A thwart consisting of a length of untrimmed twig crosses the boat about amidships, and there are fore- and after-decks which are flush with the gunwales. Stern notched for steering-oar. The stump of a mast 7.3cm high, made of an untrimmed twig like the thwart, is placed immediately forward of it. A few remnants of cordage still cling to the stump, and abreast of it the gunwales are pierced as if to take ropes. A short square steering-post has a deep groove in the top, and the base has been shaved to an octagonal section. Associated with this boat is a steering-oar; it has a one-sided blade, the back of which is in line with the loom of the oar, and it is pierced with a hole in the middle of the upper part of the blade. No other gear.

description.value: Terracotta model of an harmamaxa (covered four-wheeled wagon).  A four-wheeled carriage drawn by two horses. The equipage is driven by a man seated in a high-backed seat within the open front of the vehicle. He wears a long sleeved chiton and a hooded cloak, the hood of which covers his head, leaving the front of his hair free; he appears to be holding the reins with his right hand or perhaps both hands. The carriage has a framework of straight and curving timbers on which is constructed a tilt, indicated by incuse cross-hatching that may represent wickerwork. The sides are only partly enclosed, with a tall opening set forward on each side. The roof and the back are curved, and a square window, divided into four by cross-struts, is placed at the rear; the lower apertures of the window each have a profile head, facing one another, one perhaps female, the other probably a bearded man, and each upper opening also seems to have something within it. The body of the vehicle is sprung on timbers that curve under to the axle-plates; small curved elements shown above the rear wheels may represent the springs on which the body hung. The lower horizontal frame of the body is notched, and decorative pendants, probably jingles in the shape of bunches of grapes, hang from it at the rear. The wheels have six spokes. The horses are yoked just behind their heads, and each has a girth and breastbands, and reins to their mouths. The group is placed on a curving plinth with incuse mouldings top and bottom; the rear part of the plinth is lost and restored in plaster.   Hollow, with a cut-out below the horses’ bellies; two-piece mould.  Micaceous (very small particles) brown Nile silt. There are remains of an overall  white dressing.

description.value: Large wooden model axe with haft: possibly a toy. The form of the blade roughly imitates that of the asymmetric skewed type. Instead of lugs, there is a tang at the rear, which fits into a rectangular socket near the top of the haft. There is a hole in the tang and a corresponding one in the haft for the insertion of a dowel, now missing. A section of the lower side of the blade is abraded and there is a woodworm hole in one face. The haft is made from a nearly straight stick of wood crudely shaped for most of its length into eight or nine narrow facets. It is cracked around the socket and at the grip, which is also worn. It contains several woodworm holes. Both the blade and the haft are decorated with white, red and green paint. The faces of the blade bear a representation of a tree or branch with a red stem and green leaves on a white ground. It is surrounded by a red border. The white is much faded, having almost completely disappeared on one face, as has the red border on the cutting edge. The haft is painted along its length with alternate bands of red, white and green, and is decorated at the socket with a criss-cross pattern in red in imitation of leather binding. The rear of the tang of the blade is coloured to conform with the appearance of the haft. As on the blade much of the white on the haft has disappeared and a certain amount of the green and red has also peeled away. There is no paint left on the grip.

description.value: A hollow terracotta camel, modelled in the round and standing on a low plain plinth. Details of the head-harness are indicated in relief, as are three girth straps, although the load, a domed bundle, is shown in paint. The right hind foot and part of the plinth are lost. Two-piece mould; striations (probably post-moulding but pre-firing) show hair on the neck. Micaceous brown Nile silt, painted over much of the surface with a white dressing, except for the spaces between the legs, which are black, together with the top edges of the plinth. All the applied coloration is probably post-firing, but not certainly so. The harness, on the head and neck, the eyes, the edges of the load, its strapping and girths are all picked out in black. Other strappings of the load are painted pink and yellow. Pink is also employed on the mouth, in a stripe round the animal's throat, and in horizontal bands round its lower legs. Yellow paint is used on the plinth and between the two black harness-straps on the neck.

description.value: Blue glazed composition shabti with anthropoid coffin inscribed for Amenmes: the absence of glaze in the recesses indicates that it was self-glazed. Along the vertical band of the blue coffin, and similarly along the vertical band on the shabti's kilt, the owner's name and titles are painted in black (probably manganese). The style of Amenmes' linen dress, his curled duplex wig, and the position of his hands flat on the skirt date the figure to the Nineteenth Dynasty. Unlike the coffin, the shabti is not in the shape of a mummy, and does not hold the usual agricultural implements fot work in the Underworld. Instead he appears in the dress of daily life, perhaps to signal his rebirth as a 'sah'. Amenmes is equipped for eternity by the protective texts running around his coffin. Four horizontal bands of text, a format introduced in the New Kingdom, wrap around the coffin like mummy bandages and describe Amenmes as revered before a number of gods, including the Four Sons of Horus. For eternal protection, his image on the coffin holds the 'tyt'-girdle of Isis in his right hand, and the 'djed'-pillar of stability of the god of the Underworld, Osiris, in his left. Nut, the winged goddess of heaven, is painted across the chest of his coffin.

description.value:
Plaster head of a king, likely a sculptor’s model or trial-piece.

He wears a tall crown adorned with a uraeus cobra, its coiled body extending across the centre of the head. Its head is now lost, and directly below is a small square recess in the stone. Two small circular holes are also visible on the cobra’s right side at his head and further down his body. His eyes are almond-shaped with short cosmetic lines at the outer edges, and deep recesses that likely once held inlays. These may have been made from another material, and are now lost. His nose is short and broad at the tip, and his mouth is small and the lips are curved into a small smile. The face is rounded and fleshy, particularly at the jawline. description.value:
Limestone bust of a king, a trial piece or sculptor’s model.

The king wears a nemes headdress, with smooth lappets that extend down onto his shoulders. The body of the uraeus cobra that once adorned his forehead has been carefully removed. His ears are large and crudely modelled, and his face is long and rounded at the jawline. His eyes are narrow with thin and flat eyebrows, and his nose is slim. His thin lips are pursed together, and his face is fleshy. His chest area is smoothed into a flat plane, and his arms have not been modelled. On the sides of the bust and on the reverse are traces of a proportional grid.

There are small chips to the sides of the bust and along the nemes headdress, with larger gouges and scratches visible across the reverse. The object is now supported by a slim modern base.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta model of Archimedes screw. The lower part of a group with fieldworkers operating an Archimedes screw: only the drum and appurtenances of the screw survive. There are two bands of treads, and the left one has a surviving right foot; part of a left foot may remain on the right-hand band: two men drive the mechanism. Two curvilinear elements flank the treads. The screw-drum has circular end pieces, each with a row of small impressed points, and the bar holding the axle survives at one end. The whole terracotta group may have been produced in an elaborate two-piece mould, but a multi-piece mould to produce its constituent parts, which were then luted together, may have been employed: the complete object was probably hollow. A very few traces of a cream-coloured dressing survive.  Brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions and clay pellets.

description.value: Wooden model of a funeral barge: The hull, which is carved from a single block of sycamore wood, has a good beam in proportion to length. The bow and stern have the bent ornamental finials common in this class of boat. The deck has high gunwales which gradually merge into the solid bow, but which stop abruptly against the stern-piece. The deck is divided into nine pairs of white spaces by the thwarts and centre strip, indicated by bands of red edged with black; this centre strip may represent a hogging-beam. The main body of hull painted green, with thin black lines marking off bow and stern, which are light blue. The finials, painted yellow, are also marked off by a thin black line. The gunwales are red, thwarts and centre strip also red. Five black marks on each gunwale probably represent leather loops to take oars when rowing; vertical black marks of uncertain purpose all along inside of gunwales. Just abaft of black line between hull and bows are oculi on an oblong yellow ground outlined in black; oculi white with outlines, pupils and markings in black, in the form of a 'wedjat'-eye. There is no mast or rigging; this type of craft did not manoeuvre under sail. There are two steering-posts aft, with steering-oars in position; the larboard tiller may be a modern restoration. The steering-posts are capped with falcon-heads looking forward; they are elaborately painted, sacred wigs blue, faces yellow with black markings. Posts are painted with a filigree pattern in green, red, and blue on a white base. Steering-posts fit into square holes, falcon-heads in one piece with posts. The transverse bar is fixed with three pegs. Pegs on capitals of pillars fit into holes in canopy, feet of pillars into holes in deck. Altar glued to deck and jars glued to altar. The steering-oars with blade and loom in one piece were decorated with falcon-heads fixed to butt by pegs, colours as heads on posts; the larboard falcon-head is missing. Canopy slopes down from front to back in a gentle curve in the usual Egyptian manner; painted white with broad yellow border inside and out, front edge with vertical alternate stripes of blue, green, red, blue. Canopy supported by lotus-bud (?) columns painted with bands of yellow, green, blue, and red separated by narrower bands of white; black lines border the colour bands. Mummy white with blue wig, yellow face, eyes outlined in black. Bier yellow with broad black stripes, on both sides of the body and on the legs, imitating interlaced leather thongs. Forward of the bier is a table for offerings, painted white, on stout legs. The top is divided lengthwise with three partitions, a broad raised piece between two runnels. description.value:
Limestone model of a naos shrine.

Much of the surface is now worn, but the outline of relief figures and details are still visible. description.value: Miniature terracotta shrine with a bust of a Ptolemaic queen.  A model stele with a bust of a Ptolemaic queen, made to be used as a lamp should the purchaser so desire. It stands on a plain rectangular plinth with two wick-holes pierced in the front. The top of the stele, rising from a plain moulding, is partially broken away, but was probably rounded, with a notch cut in the front, opening up on each side at an angle, apparently producing a sort of open-fronted arcuated pediment. The queen wears a sleeveless chiton and a kalathos. Her hair is parted in the centre and falls in twisted locks onto her shoulders. By her left side is a cornucopia, its lower end impinging on the plinth. The moulding of the stele runs along each side, but the back is plain, with a pointed-arched opening to introduce the lamp-oil.  Hollow; two-piece mould with an added floor. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt with a dark-grey core. The front has a white dressing; the face of the stele is painted pink, including the cornucopia, leaving the bust white, but a diadem has been added in black paint; the kalathos is painted red, and the plinth green.
